# Accessibility Standards

## Semantic HTML First

Use native HTML elements before reaching for ARIA. Never add redundant roles.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD
<div role="button" onClick={handleClick}>Save</div>
<button role="button">Save</button>

// ✅ GOOD
<button onClick={handleClick}>Save</button>
<nav aria-label="Main navigation">...</nav>
<dialog open={isOpen}>...</dialog>
```

## Keyboard Navigation

- All interactive elements must be keyboard-focusable.
- Maintain logical tab order — avoid positive `tabIndex` values.
- `Escape` must close modals, dropdowns, and overlays.
- Custom widgets must support expected keys (e.g., arrow keys for menus, `Space`/`Enter` for toggles).

## Focus Management

- Restore focus to the trigger element when a modal/dialog closes.
- Move focus to the first interactive element on route change or panel open.
- Use `autoFocus` sparingly — only on the primary input of a newly rendered form or dialog.

## Forms

- Every `<input>` must have a visible `<label>` linked via `htmlFor`.
- Error messages must be associated via `aria-describedby`.
- Use `aria-invalid="true"` on inputs with validation errors.
- Group related fields with `<fieldset>` and `<legend>`.

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD
<label htmlFor="email">Email</label>
<input id="email" type="email" aria-describedby="email-error" aria-invalid={!!error} />
{error && <p id="email-error" role="alert">{error}</p>}
```

## Images & Media

- Meaningful images: descriptive `alt` text.
- Decorative images: `alt=""` (empty string, not omitted).
- Icon-only buttons: use `aria-label`.

## Live Regions

- `aria-live="polite"` for non-urgent status updates (toast, loading complete).
- `aria-live="assertive"` for errors that need immediate attention.
- Mount the live region container before injecting content.

## Color & Contrast

- Minimum 4.5:1 contrast ratio for normal text, 3:1 for large text.
- Never convey meaning by color alone — pair with icons, text, or patterns.

## Heading Hierarchy

- One `<h1>` per page.
- No skipped heading levels (`<h1>` → `<h3>`).
- Each section should begin with the next sequential heading level.
